THIS TRAILER CONTAINED SEVERAL DROMEDARY SHIPMENTS.  AT OUT PLATTSBURG, NY TERMINAL 1 OTHER SHIPMENT CONSISTING OF (4) FOUR #50 LB FIBER DRUMS OF PROPELLANT EXPLOSIVES, SOLID, SMOKELESS POWDER OR SMALL ARMS CLASS B EXPLOSIVES WERE ADDED, THE SHIPPING PERSONNEL PLACED THE 4 FIBER DRUMS THAT WERE LOADED ON THE REAR OF THE VAN TO BE BLOCKED AND BRACED, THE DOORS OF THE TRAILER WERE CLOSED.  SOME TIME LATER THE SECURITY GUARD MADE HER ROUNDS, DISCOVERED THERE WAS NO SEAL ON THE TRAILER SO SHE APPLIED A SEAL. THE DRIVERS ARRIVED TO PICK UP THEIR LOADED TRAILER, THEY MADE A PRE TRIP INSPECTION OF THE TRACTOR & TRAILER AS THE DOORS OF THE TRAILER WERE SEALED THE DRIVERS COULD NOT CHECK TO LOAD.  AT ARRIVAL AT ABERDEEN PROVING GROUNDS, MD IT WAS DISCOVERED THAT THE 4 FIBER DRUMS TURNED OVER AND A SMALL HOLE RUBBED IN THE SIDE OF THE FIBER DRUM AND ABOUT 1 LB. OF POWDER LEAKED OUT.  THE SPILLAGE WAS CLEANED UP AND THE FIBER DRUM WAS REPAIRED, THE 4 DRUMS WERE BLOCKED AND BRACED AND THE LOAD CONTINUED TO DESTINATION. THIS APPEARS TO BE A BREAK DOWN IN COMMUNICATIONS.

AIR BASE FIRE CREW APPLIED ABSORBENT BOOMS TO CONTAIN SPILL AREA, THEN SCOOPED APPROXIMATELY 40 GALS. OF CLEAN PRODUCT INTO BARRELS, THE APPLIED CHEMICAL FOAM AND MORE ABSORBENT PADS TO THE AREA TO CLEANUP THE AREST OF THE SPILLED PRODUCT. EIGHTY TO NINETY PERCENT OF THE SPILLED PRODUCT WAS CLEANED UP WITHIN 45 MINUTES OF THE SPILL. THE TRUAX AIR FIELD BASE IS A CONTAMINATED SITE PER THE WISCONSIN DEPARTMENT OF NATURAL RESOURCES.  MR. MIKE SCHMOLLER OF THE WISCONSIN D.N.R. WILL BE WORKING WITH THE WISCONSIN AIR NATIONAL GUARD TO ASCERTAIN THE PROPER DISPOSAL METHODS AND SITE DECONTAMINATION RELATIVE TO THIS SPILL AND THE PREVIOUSLY EXISTING CONTAMINATION.

column168: TRAILER HAD ONE PALLET ON LEFT REAR CONSISTING OF TWO 55-GALLON DRUMS OF SULFURIC ACID SHRINKWRAPPED TO PALLET.  ONE OF THE DRUMS APPEARED TO BE LEAKING.  THE SHIPPER AND CONSIGNEE WERE BOTH NOTIFIED AND CONSIGNEE SENT THEIR PEOPLE TO PLACE LEAKING DRUM INTO A RECOVERY DRUM AND CLEAN UP SPILLED PRODUCT. ALL SPILLED PRODUCT AND CONTAMINATED ITEMS (WOODEN PALLET THAT DRUMS WERE ON AND ABSORBENT USED TO CONTROL SPILL) WERE PACKED INTO RECOVERY DRUMS AND REMOVED FROM SITE BY CONSIGNEE.

AT 0700 HOURS, 2/17/1992, TRAILER WAS DISCOVERED LEAKING WHILE BEING UNLOADED FROM RAIL CAR AT GREENVILLE, TEXAS.  ALL APPROPRIATE AGENCIES NOTIFIED PLACED IN ISOLATION AT THIS TIME.  EMTECH ENVIRONMENTAL SERVICES, INC., FORT WORTH, TEXAS NOTIFIED TO RESPOND TO THE SPILL SITE. EMTECH ARRIVED ON SITE AT 1030 HOURS.  WHEN TRAILER OPENED, DISCOVERED LOAD HAD SHIFTED AND SEVERAL 5 GALLON PAILS HAD FALLEN UPSIDE DOWN AGAINST BLOCKING AT REAR OF TRAILER.  ONE PAIL HAD A SMALL LEAK FROM THE BUNG HOLE PLUG.  RESTACKED THE FALLEN PAILS AND TIGHTENED BUNG HOLE PLUG - NO DEFECT FOUND IN THE LEAKING TRAILER.  DECONTAMINATED TRAILER AND FLAT CAR, REBUILT BLOCKING AND BRACING AT REAR OF TRAILER.  COMPLETED AT 13:20 HOURS, 2/17/1992 AND LOAD FORWARDED TO DESTINATION.

DURING THE UNLOADING PROCESS, THE ASHLAND UNLOADER ENCOUNTERED A SPILL AS THE CARGO TANK EMPTIED AND THE AIR PRESSURE FROM THE UNLOADING PROCESS SURGED INTO THE TANK CAUSING THE CAUSTIC SODA TO "BUBBLE" OUT OF THE STORAGE TANK.

CUSTOMER REQUESTED DELIVERY OF 7500 GALLONS OF ISOPORPYL ALCOHOL, FLAMMABLE LIQUID, UN 1219.  MATERIAL WAS DELIVERED ON AN MC 306 AL/ FIVE COMPARTMENT 8500 GALLON CAPACITY CARGO TANK.  DURING THE OFF-LOADING SEQUENCE INTO CUSTOMER'S UNDERGROUND TANK THE QUANTITY ORDERED WOULD NOT FIT.  OUR DRIVER OVERFILLED THE TANK WITH A NET OF SPILL OF APPROXIMATELY 25 GALLONS...THE TANK WAS ONLY A 5000 GALLON TANK.  DRIVER WAS "IN ATTENDANCE" AND STOPPED THE UNLOADING.
KENAN TRANSPORT COMPANY EMPLOYEE UNLOADING AT CUSTOMER LOCATION.  NO MEANS AVAILABLE TO GAUGE TANKS.  AS DELIVERY WAS BEING COMPLETED PRODUCT BLEW OUT OF THE VENT.  PRODUCT CLEANED WITH SPILL KIT.

OUR DRIVER WAS INFORMED THAT SOME VAPOR WAS COMING OUT OF THE BACK OF THE TRAILER.  DRIVER PULLED INTO A SAFE HAVEN TO CHECK HIS TRAILER.  AFTER OPENING THE REAR CABINET DOORS, THE DRIVER NOTICED PRODUCT LEAKING BY THE FIRE CONTROL AND MANUAL VALVE FOR THE FILL AND WITHDRAWL VALVE OF THE TRAILER.  THE PRODUCT WAS SLOWLY DRIPPING DOWN ONTO THE CABINET FLOOR AND VAPORIZING.  OUR DRIVER COULD SEE NO VISIBLE CAUSE FOR THE PRODUCT PASSING THROUGH THE VALVES AS THEY WERE TIGHT.  DRIVER HAD NO CHOICE BUT TO SAFELY VENT THE PRODUCT BACK TO THE ATMOSPHERE.  TRAILER RETURNED TO NEW ORLEANS TERMINAL FOR EVALUATION.  IT WAS DETERMINED THAT THE FIRE CONTROL VALVE FAILED TO CLOSE COMPLETELY DUE TO A PIECE OF ICE PARTIALLY BLOCKING THE VALVE SEAT.  REMOVED ICE FROM VALVE AND VALVE WORKED PROPERLY.  TRAILER RETURNED TO SERVICE.
PUT IN RECOVERY DRUM AND RETURNED TO SHIPPER.

TRAILER WAS LOADED IN JACKSONVILLE, FL AND DRIVER SECURED DRUMS WITH A SINGLE LOAD LOCK.  AS VEHICLE WAS WESTBOUND ON I-10, DRIVER NOTICED A STRANGE ODOR AND PULLED INTO THE TRUCK STOP IN ROBERTSDALE, AL.  DRIVER ADVISED THAT HE TRAVELLED APPROXIMATELY THREE MILES FROM THE TIME HE NOTICED ODOR UNTIL STOPPING AT TRUCK STOP.  DRIVER OPENED HIS TRAILER AND SAW THAT A DRUM HAD FALLEN OFF OF A PALLET AND HAD A SMALL HOLE NEAR THE TOP.  DRIVER ADVISED THAT HE SET THE DRUM UP AND STRUCK A PIECE OF STICK IN THE HOLE AND STOPPED THE LEAK.  APPROXIMATELY 2 GALLONS OF PRODUCT LEAKED OUT AND ALL OF IT REMAINED IN THE TRAILER.  DRIVER CALLED THE OFFICE AND WAS ADVISED TO THROW SOME SAND INTO THE TRAILER TO CONTAIN THE SPILL AND CALL BACK FOR FURTHER INSTRUCTIONS.  BOTH THE SHIPPER AND CHEMTREC WERE CALLED AND ADVISED THAT PRODUCT COULD BE ABSORBED AND THE DRUM OVERPACKED AND THEN CARRIED ON TO RECEIVER.  A RECOVERY DRUM WAS LOCATED APPROXIMATELY 5 MILES AWAY AT WATKINS MOTOR LINES.  SINCE NO PRODUCT HAD LEFT THE TRAILER AND THE SPILL SOURCE WAS TEMPORARILY STOPPED, DRIVER WAS ADVISED TO GO TO THE WATKINS MOTOR LINES TERMINAL TO HAVE THE DAMAGED DRUM PUT IN A RECOVERY DRUM.  THE DRUM WAS OVERPACKED AND DELIVERY MADE TO RECEIVER.  THE ABSORBING MATERAIL WAS SWEPT OUT OF THE TRAILER AND PLACED INTO THE RECOVERY DRUM AT THE RECEIVER.  DRUM WAS THEN TAKEN TO WATKINS MOTOR LINES IN HOUSTON, TX TO SEEK DISPOSITION.  WE ARE WORKING WITH A COMPANY IN HOUSTON (TREATMENT 1) TO DISPOSE OF THE CONTAMINATED ABSORBING MATERIAL, BUT DO NOT HAVE DISPOSITION COMPLETED AT THIS TIME.  DRIVER HAS BEEN RESCHOOLED ON PROPER PLACEMENT OF LOAD LOCKS AND REOCCURRANCE IS UNLIKELY.

FORKLIFT OPERATOR SWUNG BLADES OF FORKLIFT INTO THE PACKAGE, TEARING OPEN THE OUTSIDE CONTAINER AND PUNCTURING THE INSIDE CONTAINER.  LOCAL FIRE MARSHAL'S OFFICE WAS CONTACTED AND RESPONDED.  RIEDEL ENVIRONMENTAL SERVICES WAS CONTACTED AND SENT RECOVERY TEAM.  MATERIAL WAS RECOUPED AND PLACED IN AN OVERPAK DRUM FOR PROPER DISPOSAL.  PERSONNEL IN NEAR VICINITY WERE SENT TO LOCAL CLINIC AS A PRECAUTION.  ALL WERE OBSERVED AND RELEASED.

DRIVER WAS INSTRUCTED TO PUT HIS LOAD IN TANK #3 AFTER CUSTOMER TOOK THEIR STICK READINGS, WHOLE LOAD DID NOT FIT & PRODUCT SPRAYED FROM VENT.  STORM DRAINS WERE AFFECTED.  CLEAN UP IS ON GOING AND ALL AGENCIES WERE NOTIFIED.

column168: A 12,000 GALLON AND A 6,000 GALLON UNDERGROUND STORAGE TANKS PIPED TOGETHER FOR THE UNLEADED PRODUCT AT THE GAS STATION.  AFTER FILLING THE 6,000 GALLON TANK THE DRIVER WAS FILLING THE 12,000 GALLON TANK, IT WAS GOING TO BE A CLOSE FIT AND AS THE PRODUCT FLOWED, THE GASOLINE STARTED TO COME OUT OF THE 6,000 GALLON TANK.  THIS CREATED A 15 GALLON SPILL (ESTIMATED BY THE DRIVER).  AT WHICH TIME THE DRIVER AND STATION MANAGER DECIDED TO CALL THE FIRE DEPARTMENT TO WASH DOWN THE AREA AND EVALUATE THE SITUATION.  THEY (FIRE DEPT.) HAD NO REAL CONCERN, AS THE WATER FROM THE WASH DOWN NEVER MADE IT TO THE STREET.  THERE WERE NO INJURIES OR PROPERTY DAMAGE. NOTE: MINNESOTA POLLUTION CONTROL WAS ALSO NOTIFIED AT 2140 HOURS ON 02-16-92.

column168: CONTAINER SCXU 145-477 WAS LOADED ON BOARD CONTAINERSHIP SS NUEVO SAN JUAN ON HER VOYAGE 129-S TO PUERTO RICO.  SHIP ENCOUNTERED HEAVY SEAS AND BOISTEROUS WEATHER EN ROUTE TO DESTINATION.  AS A RESULT, ONE PALLET OF DRUMS CORROSIVE LIQUIDS STACKED AT REAR END OF CONTAINER SHIFTED.  THE LIGHT POLYETHYLENE WRAPPING AROUND THESE DRUMS PROVED TO BE INSUFFICIENT TO PREVENT BREAKAGE OF ONE PALLET RELEASING THE DRUMS WHICH MOVED FREELY AT REAR END OF CONTAINER.  TWO OF THEM BECAME PUNCTURED WITH THE CORNER OF ONE PALLET AND RELEASED CONTENTS INSIDE CONTAINERS.  RELEASE WAS NOTICED UPON UNLOADING CONTAINER FROM VESSEL.  AN EMERGENCY CREW FROM CROWLEY ENVIRONMENTAL HANDLED THIS CASE, RECOVERING THE RELEASED MATERIAL IN OPEN DRUMS, NEUTRALIZING SAME WITH SODA ASH FOR FURTHER DISPOSITION OF SAME.

THE TRAILER WAS QUICKLY UNLOADED BACK INTO THE STORAGE TANKS, CLEAN-UP OF THE TRUCK LOADING RAMP WAS DONE WITH WATER WASH DOWN INTO THE PROPER COLLECTING SUMP.  THE EMPTY TRAILER WAS THEN MANIFESTED AS EMPTY AND TAKEN DOWN TO THE AUTHORIZED WASH FACILITY TO GET CLEANED AND GAS FREED SO THAT INSPECTION AND NECESSARY REPORTS CAN BE MADE.  IT IS SUSPECTED THAT A FRACTURE HAD DEVELOPED IN THE AREA WHERE THE LEAK WAS NOTICED.  LESS THAT 1 GALLON OF PRODUCT FELL TO THE CONCRETE DRIVE ON THE LOADING RAMP.

AT APPROXIMATELY 1000 HOURS, WEDNESDAY, FEBRUARY 12, 1992, THE TRAINMASTER AT THE CONRAIL WEST BROWNSVILLE RAIL YARD WAS NOTIFIED OF A LEAKING TANK CAR BY A DOT/FRA INSPECTOR WHO HAD OBSERVED THE LEAK.  THE LEAK WAS REPORTED AS COMING FROM THE BOTTOM OUTLET AREA OF TANK CAR PLCX-129115 (PETROLEUM NAPTHA) WHICH WAS LOCATED AT THE SOUTH END OF TRACK SEVEN AT THE WEST BROWNSVILLE YARD.  CAR WAS ISOLATED AND CHEMTREC AND THE LOCAL AAR/BUREAU OF EXPLOSIVES INSPECTOR WERE NOTIFIED.  A BUCKET WAS PLACED UNDER THE OUTLET WHICH WAS LEAKING ONE DROP OF PRODUCT APPROXIMATELY EVERY THIRTY SECONDS. AAR/BUREAU OF EXPLOSIVES SENIOR INSPECTOR T. MANNAS ARRIVED TO THE LOCATION OF THE TANK CAR AT APPROXIMATELY 14:30 HOURS, 02/14/92, AND WAS ABLE TO SECURE THE LEAK BY TIGHTENING THE FOUR STUDS BOLTS SECURING THE VALVE TO THE TANK CAR SHELL.  REPRESENTATIVES FROM THE CONSIGNEE (GE SPECIALITY CHEMICALS) ALSO RESPONDED AND INSPECTED THE CAR AFTER THE REPAIRS WERE MADE.  CAR WAS CLEARED TO DESTINATION AT APPROXIMATELY 17:30 HOURS, 02/12/92. SHIPPER (EXXON) WAS ADVISED BY SENIOR INSPECTOR MANNAS THAT THE CAR'S BOTTOM OUTLET VALVE SHOULD BE THROUGHLY INSPECTED PRIOR TO RELOADING.

AN UNKNOWN SUBSTANCE WAS FOUND ON THE FLOOR OF A DEDICATED HAZARDOUS WASTE TRAILER.  LABORATORY ANALYSIS INDICATED THE MATERIAL WAS NICKEL SULFATE. IT APPEARED AS IF APPROXIMATELY ONE GALLON OF MATERIAL HAD SPILLED.  THIS TRAILER HAS A STEEL SECONDARY CONTAINMENT PAN THUS PREVENTING ANY RELEASE OF MATERIAL OUTSIDE THE TRAILER.  IT IS UNKNOWN HOW OR WHY THE RELEASE OCCURRED.  SUNBELT INDUSTRIAL SERVICE OF SPRINGFIELD, MO WAS CONTRACTED TO PROPERLY DECONTAMINATE THE TRAILER FLOOR.  IT IS BELIEVED THE SHIPPER WAS ASHLAND CHEMICAL, INC OF SHAKOPEE, MN AND THE CONSIGNEE, CHEMICAL WASTE MANAGEMENT, INC., EMELLE, AL.

DRUM WAS TAKEN OFF TAIL END OF TRUCK AND PLACED NEXT TO A METAL PALLET.  A FORKLIFT REMOVING OTHER FREIGHT, BACKED UP AND STRUCK THE DRUM WHICH WAS PUSHED AGAINST THE PALLET.  THE DRUM WAS SEVERLY DENTED AND BEGAN LEAKING THROUGH A SMALL CRACK ON THE BOTTOM RIM.  APPROXIMATELY 1.5 GALLONS LEAKED BEFORE THE DRUM WAS TURNED TO FACE THE HOLE UPWARDS.  THIS STOPPED THE LEAKAGE. NO CLEANUP WAS ATTEMPTED SINCE THE LIQUID EVAPORATED VERY QUICKLY.  THE DRUM WAS CAREFULLY MOVED OUTSIDE OF THE BUILDING CLEAR OF PERSONNEL AND MACHINERY.  THE SHIPPER RECOVERED THE DRUM AND CONTENTS THE FOLLOWING DAY.  THIS INCIDENT AND CORRECT HANDLING PROCEDURES WERE REVIEWED WITH DOCK PERSONNEL HAS A PREVENTATIVE MEASURE.

WHEN UNLOADING A PALLET FROM TRAILER AT CF DOCK, FORKLIFT OPERATOR PUNCTURED A 55 GAL DRUM IN FRONT OF THE PALLET.  AFTER BACKING OUT OF THE TRAILER IT WAS NOTICED THE DRUM WAS LEAKING SLOWLY.  APPROXIMATELY 1 GALLON OF LESS HAD STARTED TO LEAK.  THE DRUM WAS IMMEDIATELY LAID ON ITS SIDE TO STOP LEAKING.  LEAKAGE WAS ABSORBED WITH ABSORB-ALL GRANUALES. CHEMTREC WAS NOTIFIED BY CF SUPERVISOR SEAN GRIFFIN ADN FOUND MATERIAL TO BE A PAINT THINNER - PUNCTURED DRUM & ABSORB-ALL WERE TRANSFERRED TO OVERPAK DRUM - CONSIGNEE WAS CALLED AND ACCEPTED FREIGHT.

column168: DRIVER WAS PRECEEDING TO THE LEFT IN A CURVE.  RIGHT FRONT AND REAR WHEELS LEFT THE RIGHT SIDE OF THE ROAD.  DRIVER ATTEMPTED TO PULL BACK ONTO THE ROAD SURFACE AND OVER-CONTROLLED, HEADING FOR THE LEFT SIDE OF THE ROAD. DRIVER THEN ATTEMPTED TO SHARPLY TURN VEHICLE BACK TO THE RIGHT.  VEHICLE WAS ROLLED ONTO ITS SIDE ADN SLID DOWN ROADWAY COMING TO A STOP.  PRESSURE GAUGE ON ONE TANK WAS SHEARED OFF WHEN FIRE EXTINGUISHER BROKE LOOSE AND STRUCK THE PRESSURE GAUGE. APPROXIMATELY 50 GALLONS OF PROPANE WAS SPILLED BEFORE LEAK WAS STOPPED. WHILE VEHICLE WAS ON ITS SIDE, PRESSURE GAUGE OPENING WAS IN LIQUID SPACE, VENTING LIQUID.  VEHICLE WAS TURNED UPRIGHT PUTTING OPENING IN VAPOR SPACE.  OPENING WAS THEN PLUGGED, STOPPING FLOW OF GAS.  ALL GAS DISPERSED IN THE ATMOSPHERE.

ON 2-13-92 DELTA DISTRIBUTORS INC WAS MAKING A DELIVERY TO AUTOMOTIVE COMPONENT GROUP AT MILHAVEN AND LOVE ROAD IN MONROE, LA 71201.  THE SHIPMENT CONSISTED OF 8 DRUMS (55 GALLONS EACH) OF SODIUM HYDROXIDE LIQUID.  WHEN THE DRIVER (JEFF CRIVELLO) OPENED THE DOORS TO UNLOAD THE MATERIAL HE IMMEDIATELY SAW ONE DRUM OF SODIUM HYDROXIDE LIQUID LEAKING ON FLOOR OF TRAILER.  IMMEDIATELY THE DRIVER AND PLANT PERSONNEL CONTAINED THE SPILL AND PUT THE LEAKING DRUM INTO A 80 GALLON OVERPACK. THE WASTE GENERATED FROM THE CLEANUP WILL BE DISPOSED OF IN COMPLIANCE WITH EPA REGULATIONS.

column168: WAS ADVISED BY MR. JAMES DUNN, TERMINAL TRAINMASTER, SOO-KCS JOINT AGENCY, THAT TANK CAR UTLX 86961, LOAD, MONOETHANOLAMINE WAS OBSERVED OVER THE WEEKEND BY SWITCH CREW TO BE LEAKING FROM TOP FITTINGS. TANK CAR WAS ISOLATED.  INSPECTION REVEALED THAT APPROXIMATELY 8 INCHES OF THE MANWAY GASKET, WHICH WAS TORN, HAD BECOME MISPLACED AND WAS HANGING INTO THE MANWAY NOZZLE.  DID NOT HAVE A PROPER GASKET ON HAND, SO OBTAINED ONE FROM ACF INDUSTRIES TANK CAR SHOP IN NORTH KANSAS CITY, MO.  THIS GASKET WAS NOT THE PROPER SIZE.  DECIDED AGAINST USING "GORTEX" MATERIAL TO GASKET THE CLOSURE, SO CONTACTED THE SHIPPER, TEXACO CHEMICAL, PT. NECHES, TEXAS THROUGH CHEMTREC TO REQUEST ASSISTANCE IN GETTING A PROPER GASKET. WAS PUT IN CONTACT WITH EMERGENCY RESPONSE PERSONNEL WHO ADVISED THEY RESPOND WITH A GASKET. RESPONSE PERSONNEL ARRIVED THE MORNING OF THE 4TH.  THE GASKETS THEY BROUGHT WERE NOT THE PROPER SIZE.  OBTAINED A GASKET FROM HANNA RUBBER COMPANY, KANSAS CITY, WHICH WAS INSTALLED AT APPROXIMATELY 11:30 AM. WASHED SPILLED LIQUID FROM CAR, RESEALED MANWAY COVER AND CLOSED-SYSTEM PROTECTIVE HOUSING AND RELEASED CAR AT APPROXIMATELY 12 NOON ON THE 4TH. SHIPMENT WAS CONTRARY TO SECTIONS 173.31(B)(3), 179.200-15(D) AND 179.200-16(A), TITLE 49 CFR AND SECTION A4.03(F) OF THE ASSOCIATION OF AMERICAN RAILROADS SPECIFICATIONS FOR TANK CARS FOR NOT EQUIPPING THE MANWAY COVER/NOZZLE JOINT WITH AN EFFECTIVE GASKET AND FAILURE TO APPLY A CLOSURE PLUG TO THE 1/4 INCH TELL-TALE GAUGING DEVICE (PLUG WAS SUPPLIED BY THIS INSPECTOR). THESE EXCEPTIONS WERE DISCUSSED WITH THE SHIPPER RESPONSE PERSONNEL.

I REMOVED DUST CAP FROM VALVE TO FIND FROZEN MATERIAL IN OUTLET I ASSUMED AT THAT TIME IT WAS WATER FROM TANK WASH.  WHILE WAITING FOR SAMPLE RESULTS.  I WENT AHEAD AND GOT HOSE OUT TO UNLOAD AT THE CUSTOMER SITE. INSIDE THE DIKE WHERE I HAD TO HOOK HOSE UP HAD LOTS OF WATER LAYING AROUND.  SO I WENT AROUND DRIVER SIDE OF TRUCK AND GOT OUT SAFETY GEAR (MY RUBBER BOOTS WHERE STIFF FROM COLD WEATHER (TEMP WAS APPROX 10-15 DEGREES)) SO I THREW THEM INSIDE THE CAB TO WARM UP SO THEY WOULD STRETCH OVER MY SHOES.  NO VALVES WERE OPENED BY ME AND NO HOOK UPS WERE MADE SO AT THAT TIME THERE WAS NO CONCERN ABOUT ANYTHING LEAKING.  I COULDN'T START PUMPING UNTIL SAMPLE WAS OKAYED.  I PUT MY BOOTS AND SUIT ON AND WALKED AROUND TRUCK AND THATS WHEN I SAW THE CAUSTIC RUNNING ON THE GROUND. KNOWING THAT THERE WAS NO VALVE OPEN THE ONLY THING I COULD DO WAS TO STUFF THE CAP ON THE OUTLET THEN I RAN UP TO THE OFFICE AND NOTIFIED THE CUSTOMER.  THEY RESPONDED QUICKLY AND WE CONTAINED THE SPILL BEFORE IT RAN INTO ANY DRAINS.  THE CUSTOMER SUCKED THE PRODUCT UP. AND PUT ABSORB-ALL ON PRODUCT.  LATER THEY DISCOVERED CAUSTIC IN THE CREEK BESIDE THEIR PROPERTY.  THEY SAID THE CAUSTIC SEEPED THROUGH THE BLOCK TO THE GROUND UNDERNEATH IS POROUS AND RAN INTO THE CRACK - ONE WORKER MADE THE COMMENT THAT THERE WAS A LIMING UNDER THE BLACK TOP.  MEASURING THE TANK (056) IT WAS DETERMINED APPROXIMATELY 35 GALLONS WAS LOST.

column168: THE SEABORD TANK LINES, INC. DRIVER WAS LOADING GASOLINE AT THE CHEVRON LOADING RACK.  THE DRIVER WAS BOTTOM LOADING THREE GRADES OF GASOLINE BY THE BOTTOM LOADING METHOD.  HE HAD SET A COUPLER ON HIS CARGO TANK LOADING LINE FROM RACK #3.  THE COUPLER WAS DEFECTIVE, SO HE RETURNED IT TO ITS PLACE AND THEN TOOK A COUPLER FROM RACK #4.  HE MISTAKENLY SET THE METER FOR RACK #3 TO LOAD HIS CARGO TANK THRU.  WHEN HE ACTIVATED THE #3 METER TO LOAD HIS TRAILER, THE PRESSURE AGAINST THE CLOSED LOADING ARM FROM #3 CAUSED TO INTERNAL POPPIT ON THE LOADING ARM TO BLOW OUT HE SHUT THE METER DOWN AS SOON AS HE SAW WHAT HAPPENED.  HE THEN SQUEEZED THE PRODUCT INTO THE RACK DRAINAGE TRENCH SO NO PRODUCT LEFT THE RACK AREA.  THE CHEVRON PERSONNEL AND GULF OIL PERSONNEL WERE NOTIFIED AND CAME TO THE AREA.  THE AREA WAS CLEANED DOWN BY THE CHEVRON FIRE DEPT.  ALL PRODUCT WENT INTO CHEVRON'S HOLDING TANKS AND NO PRODUCT WAS LOST IN THE ENVIRONMENT.

column25: DU PONT E I DE NEMOURS & CO
column168: TANK CAR WAS APPROXIMATELY SIX HOURS INTO PROCESS OF BEING SAFELY OFFLOADED WHEN A LIQUID UNLOADING HOSE RUPTURED.  PERSONNEL ATTENDING UNLOADING OPERATION WERE UTILIZING A VIDEO MONITOR LOCATED IN THE PROCESS CONTROL ROOM AND IMMEDIATELY CLOSED BOTH EMERGENCY BLOCK (SHUT-OFF) VALVES WHICH STOPPED THE RELEASE.  THEY THEN ACTIVATED THE PLANT GAS RELEASE HORN, NOTIFIED SITE SECURITY AND DONNED PERSONAL PROTECTIVE EQUIPMENT TO CLOSE MANUAL VALVES ON BOTH THE TANK CAR AND THE UNLOADING LINE.  DURATION OF RELEASE IS ESTIMATED TO HAVE BEEN APPROXIMATELY TEN SECONDS. IMMEDIATE CAUSE OF INCIDENT WAS THE FAILURE (RUPTURE) OF ONE OF THE TWO 1-1/2 INCH FLEXIBLE UNLOADING HOSES BEING UTILIZED.  ACTION TAKEN TO PREVENT FUTURE INCIDENTS OF THIS TYPE INCLUDE: 1.) INSTALLED A RIGID PIPE UNLOADING LINE TO FINISH UNLOADING THIS TANK CAR. 2.) COMMENCED STUDY TO EVALUATE A PERMANENT FIXED PIPE UNLOADING SYSTEM FOR UNLOADING FUTURE TANK CARS OF THIS MATERIAL.

EMPLOYEE WAS UNLOADING TRAILER AND NOTICED LEAKING BUCKETS.  NO APPARENT DAMAGE, SEEMED TO BE A PACKAGING FAILURE.  THE SHIPPER WAS CONTACTED (PAT KELVRY).  THE PROBLEM WAS EXPLAINED AND THE PRODUCT RETURNED TO EVALUATION.

WHILE AIR UNLOADING OFF PRODUCT FROM TANK TRAILER THE UNLOADING HOSE DEVELOPED A PIN HOLE LEAK.  DRIVER IMMEDIATELY SHUT UNLOADING VALVE AND PUT BUCKET UNDER LEAK IN HOSE. HE HELPED SHOVEL SPILLED PRODUCT AND SODA ASH INTO DRUM (2 GALLONS WERE CONTAINED IN 5 GALLON BUCKET).  MILPORT CHEMICAL NOTIFIED THE LOCAL DEPT. OF NATURAL RESOURCES.

column168: VEHICLE WAS TRAVELING EN ROUTE TO DESTINATION WHEN A DRIVER BEHIND THE VEHICLE NOTICED LIQUID DRIPPING UNDER THE TRUCK. SEATTLE FIRE, POLICE AND ENGINEERING PERSONNEL, ALONG WITH BURLINGTON ENVIRONMENTAL SPILL RESPONSE PERSONNEL, CLEANED UP THE REMAINING MATERIAL ON THE ROAD BY ABSORBING & SWEEPING. column168: ON FEBRUARY 7, 1992, OUR DRIVER PERFORMED HIS INTRA-TRIP VEHICLE INSPECTION WHILE PARKED AT THE BUCKEYE TRAVELERS MALL TRUCK STOP, NOTICED A CLEAR LIQUID SLOWLY DRIPPING FROM THE REAR, LEFT SIDE LOWER TAILGATE OF THE ROLL OFF CONTAINER THAT HE WAS TRANSPORTING.  THE DRIVER NOTIFIED OUR COMPANY OF THE DRIPPING AND OUR COMPANY DISPATCHED PERSONNEL TO THE TRUCK STOP TO HANDLE ANY CLEAN UP. THE CONTAINER HELD 25,960 POUNDS OF A HAZARDOUS WASTE SOLID, NOS ORM-E NA9189, SPECIFICALLY AN INCINERATOR ASH IDENTIFIED AT RCRA EPA HAZARDOUS WASTE NUMBERS F002, F003 AND F005.  THE OHIO EPA EMERGENCY RESPONSE CENTER AND THE OHIO EPA NORTHWEST DISTRICT OFFICE WAS NOTIFIED OF THE EVENT AND SENT A REPRESENTATIVE TO THE LOCATION. ENVIROSAFE SERVICES OF OHIO, INC (ESOI) PERSONNEL ARRIVED AT THE LOCATION, RESEALED THE TAILGATE AND CLEANED UP ALL DRIPPED MATERIAL AND DECOMTAMINATED THE AFFECTED AREA OF THE TRAILER.  APPROXIMATELY 330 MILLILITERS OF LIQUID HAD DRIPPED FROM THE CONTAINER AND AN ESTIMATED 10 POUNDS OF TOTAL SOILS WERE REMOVED.  THE OHIO EPA EMERGENCY RESPONSE COORDINATOR PRESIDED OVER THE CLEAN UP AND APPROVED OF ALL ACTIONS TAKEN. THE CLEANED UP MATERIAL (SOIL, PADS, SORBENT, PPE) WERE DRUMMED AND TAKEN TO THE ESOI TSDF SITE AT 876 OTTER CREEK ROAD, OREGON, OH FOR DISPOSAL. THE VEHICLE LEFT THE TRUCK AND PROCEEDED TO THE ESOI TSDF. THERE WERE NO INJURIES AS A RESULT OF THIS INCIDENT.

column168: APPROXIMATELY 30 POUNDS OF PETROLEUM AND METAL HYDROXIDE FILTER CAKE SOLIDS [RQ, HAZARDOUS WASTE, SOLID, NOS, ORM-E NA 9189 (D006, D007, D008, D009, WP03)] WAS ALLEGEDLY RELEASED FROM THE TAILGATE ONTO A TARP WITH NO RELEASE TO THE ENVIRONMENT.  THE DRIVER HAD STOPPED ON I-205 NEAR VANCOUVER, WA FOR A ROUTINE SAFETY INSPECTION AND NOTICED THE "DOGS" ON THE TAILGATE WERE NOT PROPERLY CLOSED (FUSE HAD BLOWN).  THE SAFETY CHAINS PREVENTED THE TAILGATE FROM OPENING MORE THAN ABOUT ONE INCH AND A PLASTIC LINER IN THE DUMP BED CONTAINED THE LOAD.  AS THE DRIVER WAS SECURING THE DOGS, THE WASHINGTON STATE DOT ARRIVED AND THEN CALLED THE STATE POLICE FOR A POTENTIAL RELEASES OF HAZARDOUS WASTE.  IN SECURING THE DOGS, ROAD DIRT HAD FALLEN ONTO THE TARP PLACED UNDER THE TAILGATE BY THE DRIVER. THIS IS WHAT APPARENTLY PROMPTED THE WADOT TO NOTIFY THE STATE POLICE WHO IN TURN NOTIFIED THE WA DEPT OF ECOLOGY.  THE TARP AND THE MATERIAL WERE PLACED INTO THE DUMP BED AND THE STATE POLICE ISSUED THE DRIVER A CITATION AND RELEASSED THE VEHICLE. THE INFORMATION SPECIFIC TO A TARP BEING PLACED UNDER THE TAILGATE AND LACK OF AN ACTUAL RELEASE OF THE LOAD WAS NOT AVAILABLE UNTIL THE DRIVER REACHED CSSI-ARLINGTON SEVERAL HOURS LATER.  BASED ON THE RQ (1 POUND), A RELEASES TO THE ENVIRONMENT WOULD BE IMMEDIATELY REPORTABLE UNDER CERCLA, SARA, RCRA AND WASHINGTON STATE REGULATIONS AND AS SUCH WAS REPORTED PROMPTLY.  AS THIS INCIDENT WAS REPORTED UNDER CERCLA AND WAS, A USDOT HAZARDOUS MATERIAL INCIDENT REPORT DESCRIBING THE CIRCUMSTANCES HAS BEEN SUBMITTED TO THE USDOT AND COPIED TO THE WUTC.

column168: DOME LID WAS NOT SECURED.  AS ENROUTE TO CUSTOMER, A SMALL AMOUNT OF PRODUCT WAS RELEASED.  THE SPILL WAS CONTAINED AND CLEANED UP.  ALL NECESSARY REGULATORY AGENCIES WERE NOTIFIED.

THE DRIVER PICKED UP A PRELOADED TRAILER AT THE LOADING FACILITY IN CENTERVILLE, UT.  AFTER PERFORMING A PROPER PRE-TRIP INSEPCTION, HE DEPARTED FOR GOLCONDA, NV HIS DELIVERY DESTINATION.  HIS ROUTE OF TRAVEL CONSISTED OF I-80 WEST TO THE GOLCONDA EXIT, SOME 350 MILES WEST OF CENTERVILLE, UT.  TIRE AND EQUIPMENT INSPECTIONS WERE PERFORMED AT THE PROPER INTERVALS, WITH THE LAST INSPECTION AT THE GOLCONDA EXIT.  AT EACH OF THESE INSPECTIONS THE EQUIPMENT WAS IN GOOD SHAPE WITH NO LEAKS.  THE DELIVERY LOCATION IS 26 MILES FROM THE INTERSTATE, OF WHICH ONLY 12 MILES IS A PAVED ROAD.  THE LAST 14 MILES IS A SOLID DIRT ROAD, WHICH HAD A WASHBOARD SURFACE.  DUE TO THIS SURFACE THE FILL VALVE VIBRATED PARTIALLY OPEN, ALLOWING LIQUID OXYGEN TO LEAK ON THE FLOOR OF THE CABINET WHICH OVERVILLED AND LEAKED ON TO THE TIRES, BLOWING OUT A TIRE.  THE DRIVER TIGHTENED THE VALVE, WHICH STOPPED THE LEAK.  A ROAD CALL WAS PERFORMED TO REPLACED THE TIRE AND THE TRIP CONTINUED WITHOUT FURTHER INCIDENT. column168: LOAD SHIFTED IN TRANSIT, NOT BLOCKED OR SECURED PROPERLY, SPEED ALSO MAY HAVE BEEN A FACTOR, BEING INVESTIGATED.  PROPER AUTHORITIES CALLED AND RESPONDED, SEE SUMMARY.  ADDITIONAL TRAINING TO BE GIVEN, PROCEDURES HAVE BEEN WRITTEN.  A NEW TRAILER IS BEING DESIGNED.  SUMMARY - AT 9:49A.M. ON TUESDAY, FEBRUARY 11, 1992, A PRATT & WHITNEY TRACTOR- TRAILER TRANSPORTING HAZARDOUS WASTE LIQUID FROM NORTH HAVEN TO EAST HARTFORD FOR TREATMENT OVERTURNED WHEN TURNING THE CORNER NEAR THE RUNWAY AND THE OBB PARKING LOT IN EAST HARTFORD.  SECURITY, THE P & W FIRE DEPARTMENT, MEDICAL, ENVIRONMENTAL AND HEALTH & SAFETY WERE NOTIFIED AND IMMEDIATELY ON THE SCENE.  THE DRIVER WAS TAKEN TO PRATT & WHITNEY MEDICAL AND SENT TO MANCHESTER MEMORIAL HOSPITAL FOR OBSERVATION.  HE WAS NOT ADMITTED.  THE MANIFEST WAS OBTAINED BY THE FIRE DEPT. AND PRESENTED TO ENVIRONMENTAL UPON ARRIVAL.  THE TRACTOR-TRAILER TRUCK CONTAINED ONE 220 GALLON AND SEVEN 330 GALLON TRANSPORTERS OC COMPATIBLE LIQUIDS.  ACCORDING TO THE MAINFEST, FIVE CONTAINED SODIUM HYDROZIDE AND THREE CONTAINED A NICKEL STRIPPING SOLUTION.  TWO TRANSPORTERS LEAKED A MAZIMUM OF 400 GALLONS OF THE NICKEL STRIPPING SOLUTION.  THE EAST HARTFORD FIRE DEPT., LOCAL EMERGENCY PLANNING COMMITTEE, CONNECTICUT DEPARTMENT OF ENVIRONMENTAL PROTECTION, THE CONNECTICUT DEPARTMENT OF TRANSPORTATION, AND THE NATIONAL RESPONSE CENTER WERE NOTIFIED.  ALL RESPONDED EXCEPT FOR THE NRC AND THE DOT.  THE LIQUID LEAKED SLOWLY ONTO THE ASPHALT ROAD.  SODIUM BICARBONATE WAS APPLIED TO NEUTRALIZE THE SPILLED MATERIAL.  A SAND DIKE WAS USED TO PREVENT THE LIQUID FROM REACHING ANY DRAINS.  BECAUSE OF THE QUANTITY OF LIQUID INVOLVED (APPROX. 3000 GALLONS), ENVIRONMENTAL PERSONNEL DECIDED TO BRING IN A HAZARDOUS WASTE CONTRACTOR, CLEAN HARBORS, EQUIPPED WITH A TANKER TRUCK TO HANDLE THE MAJORITY OF THE CLEAN-UP AND DISPOSAL.  IN AN ATTEMPT TO CONTAIN THE SPILL UNTIL THE CONTRACTOR ARRIVED, TRAINED PRATT & WHITNEY PERSONNEL SUITED UP TO LEVEL B PERSONAL PROTECTIVE EQUIPMENT (TYVEX SUITS AND SCOTT AIR PACKS) AND VACUUMED THE SPILLING LIQUID INTO A PORTABLE ELLIOT TANK.  UPON THE CONTRACTOR'S ARRIVAL, A BOOM CRANE SUPPLIED BY P & W REMOVED THE TRANSPORTERS FROM WITHIN THE TRAILER ONE-BY-ONE AND STOOD THEM UPRIGHT TO BE PUMPED INTO THE TANKER TRUCK.  AT APPROZIMATELY 3:00 P.M., HUGHES BROTHERS TOWING OF WETHERSFIELD ARRIVED WITH TWO LARGER DROTT CRANES TO COMPLETE THE REMOVAL OF THE TRANSPORTERS AND TO UPRIGHT THE TRACTOR AND TRAILER.  THE TRACTOR-TRAILER WAS TURNED UPRIGHT AT APPROXIMATELY 5:00 P.M. AND TOWED TO A PAD AT WASTE TREATMENT FOR DECONTAMINATION THE FOLLOWING DAY.  CLEAN HARBORS FINISHED THE CLEAN-UP AND LEFT COMPANY PROPERTY AT APPROXIMATELY 7:30 P.M.

WHILE AT THE CUSTOMER UNLOADING, AFTER A NORMAL PUMP COOLDOWN AND UNLOADING OVER 300 GALLONS OF LIQUID NITROGEN, THE TRAILER STARTED LEAKING LIQUID NITROGEN PAST THE SEAT ON THE MAIN FILL VALVE.  THE DRIVER ATTEMPTED TO CLOSE DOWN ON THE VALVE TO STOP THE LEAK WITHOUT SUCCESS.  THE DRIVR STOPPED THE UNLOADING PROCEDURE AND REDUCED THE VESSEL PRESSURE AND STILL THE LEAK CONTINUED.  A DECISION WAS MADE TO CONTINUE TO UNLOAD THE PRODUCT INTO THE CUSTOMER TANK AS THIS WOULD BE THE FASTEST PROCEDURE TO STOP THE LEAK.  AFTER UNLOADING THE LEAK WAS CONTAINED. UPON ARRIVAL BACK AT THE TERMINAL, A COMPLETE INSPECTION OF THE ENTIRE VALVE IN QUESTION WAS PERFORMED, NO VALVE DEFECTS WERE FOUND TO EXIST.  IT IS PRESUMED THAT DUE TO THE RAINS AND THE MOISTURE IN THE AIR AN ICE BLOCK FORMED ON THE SEAT OF THE VALVE DURING THE FILLING PROCEDURE.  DURING THE PUMP COOLDOWN AND UNLOADING, THE TRAILER PRESSURE IS INCREASED FROM 5 PSIG TO 30 PSIG AND THIS INCREASED PRESSURE CAUSED THE ICE BLOCKAGE TO PARTIALLY BREAK LOOSE, ALLOWING NITROGEN TO ESCAPE THROUGH THE VALVE SEAT AREA.

ENSCO, INC. LOCATED IN EL DORADO ARKANSAS, REJECTED 4-30 GALLON POLYETHYLENE ("POLY") DRUMS BACK TO CLEAN HARBORS OF NATICK, INC LOCATED AT 10 MERCER ROAD IN NATICK, MA. 01760.  THE 4-30 GALLON POLY OPEN HEAD DRUMS CONTAINED BETWEEN 10-15, 1 GALLON CONTAINERS OF THIONYL CHLORIDE. THE DRIVER OF THE VEHICLE STOPPED HIS VEHICLE AT THE NORTH LITTLE ROCK "76" TRUCK STOP ON I-40 AND GALLOWAY - EXIT 161 AND CONDUCTED A LOAD/TIRE CHECK.  IT WAS AT THIS TIME THAT HE NOTICED FUMES ESCAPING FROM THE TRAILER'S BACK DOOR.  THE DRIVER IMMEDIATELY NOTIFIED A CLEAN HARBOR TERMINAL, WHO THEN IMMEDIATELY NOTIFIED THE ARKANSAS STATE POLICE.  THE ARKANSAS STATE POLICE DISPATCHED THE LITTLE ROCK FIRE AND POLICE DEPARTMENT, WHO UPON ARRIVAL AT THE SCENE, MOVED THE TRUCK TO A REMOTE SECTION OF THE TRUCK STOP AND RESTRICTED ACCESS TO THE AREA.  THE FIRE CHIEF PROVIDED THE NAME OF A LOCAL SPILL CONTRACTOR IN THE EVENT CLEAN HARBORS COULD NOT MOBILIZE A CREW IN A TIMELY MANNER.  DUE TO THE DISTANCE TO THE NEAREST CLEAN HARBORS EMERGENCY RESPONSE GROUP IT WAS DECIDED THAT SPILL TECH SERVICES OUT OF LITTLE ROCK, AR. WOULD PERFORM THE RESPONSE. TECHNICIANS FROM SPILL TECH ENTERED THE VEHICLE UNDER LEVEL A PROTECTION AND DISCOVERED THAT ONE OF THE LIDS FROM A 30 GALLON CONTAINER HAD DISLODGED DUE TO THE BUILD-UP OF PRESSURE UNDER THE LID.  IT WAS DISCOVERED THAT THE CLOSURES ON 3-4 CONTAINERS PACKED INSIDE THE 30 GALLON DRUM HAD FAILED AND THE THIONYL CHLORIDE BEGAN TO FUME ON CONTACT WITH RESIDUAL MOISTURE IN THE VERMICULITE THAT WAS USED AS PACKING MATERIAL. SPILL TECH REPACKAGED ALL THE DAMAGED CONTAINERS AND REPACKED THE DRUMS IN THE 30 GALLON CONTAINERS.  EACH 30 GALLON DRUM WAS THEN OVERPACKED INTO 85 GALLON SALVAGE DRUMS AS A PRECAUTION.  ALL MATERIAL THAT WAS GENERATED AS A RESULT OF THE RESPONSE WAS MANIFESTED TO CLEAN HARBORS OF NATICK WHERE IT WILL BE UTIMATELY DISPOSED OF AT A PROPERLY LICENSED DISPOSAL FACILITY. THERE WERE NO INJURIES AS A RESULT OF THE INCIDENT NOR WAS THERE ANY DAMAGE TO THE TRUCK STOP.  IN ORDER TO PREVENT THIS INCIDENT FROM RECURRING, CLEAN HARBORS OF NATICK HAS PROVIDED REFRESHER TRAINING AND INSTRUCTION TO ALL FIELD PERSONNEL WHO HANDLE POTENTIALLY REACTIVE MATERIALS.  THE TRAINING INCLUDED PROPER PACKING PROCEDURES, INSPECTION OF ALL CONTAINERS TO CHECK THE INTEGRITY OF THE CLOSURE DEVICE AND OVERPACKING PROCEDURES.  IN ADDITION, ALL SPECIAL PROJECTS DEALING WITH REACTIVE MATERIALS WILL HAVE DETAILED WORK PLAN ESTABLISHED PRIOR TO INITIAITON OF THE PROJECT.  THIS PLAN WILL INCLUDE A DESCRIPTION OF THE MATERIAL BEING HANDLED, SPECIAL HANDLING PRECAUTIONS, HEALTH AND SAFETY INFORMATION AND A DETAILED WORK DESCRIPTION.

column168: THE ACCIDENT/INCIDENT WAS THE RESULT OF A LARGE PACKAGE (6X6X16) BEING LOADED ON AN ORDINARY FLAT BED TRAILER WHICH CREATED A HIGH CENTER OF GRAVITY AND RENDERED THE SECUREMENT DEVICES INADEQUATE TO RESTRAIN THE CARGO.  THE SHIPMENT WAS LOADED BY AND ON A TRAILER PROVIDED BY THE SHIPPER.  WHEN THE LOAD WAS PICKED UP BY THE CARRIER'S DRIVER, HE PROVIDED THE SECUREMENT DEVICES REQUIRED BY 49 CFR 393.100(B)(2), AND DID NOT REALIZE THAT THE CARGO HAD NOT BEEN BLOCKED AND BRACED IN ACCORDANCE WITH 49 CFR 393.104(B).  IN TRANSIT WHILE NEGOTIATING A CURVE, THE PACKAGE SHIFTED AND THE MOVEMENT OF THE CARGO COUPLED WITH THE HIGH CENTER OF GRAVITY AND THE CENTRIFUGAL FORCES RESULTING FROM THE VEHICLE NEGOTIATING A CURVE CAUSED THE VEHICLE TO OVERTURN.  THERE WAS NO BREACH OF CONTAINMENT, LOSS OF PRODUCT OR CONTAMINATION.  THE PACKAGE WAS LOADED ON ANOTHER VEHICLE AND RETURNED TO THE SHIPPER.  FUTURE MOVEMENTS OF THIS TYPE CONTAINER WILL BE MADE ON DROP FRAME (LOW-BOY) TYPE TRAILERS AND VERIFICATION OF ALL REQUIRED SECUREMENT DEVICES INCLUDING BLOCKING AND BRACING WILL BE PERFORMED PRIOR TO DEPARTURE.

column168: ON FEBRUARY 26, 1992, QUADREL BROS. CONTACTED TIER, INC. ABOUT CLEANUP AND DISPOSAL OF SPENT SULFURIC ACID RESIDUES RESULTING FROM AN OVER-TURNED TRACTOR TRAILER CONTAINING THIS MATERIAL.  TIER WAS CONTRACTED BY QUADREL BROS. TO CONDUCT A SITE ASSESSMENT OF THE AREA AFFECTED AND COMPLETE THE CLEANUP OF ANY SPILLED SPENT SULFURIC ACID REMAINING AT THE SITE. ARRANGEMENTS WERE MADE WITH MIKE RYBACKI FO PADER TO MEET AT THE SITE OF THE SPILL, WHICH WAS 1/2 MILE SOUTH OF THE WOODHAVEN EXIT ON I-95 SOUTH ON FEBRUARY 28, 1992. MIKE RYBACKI REQUESTED PH READING OF THE SOIL IN THE AFFECTED AREA OF THE SPILL AND FROM AN ADJACENT AREA FOR A BACKGROUND READING.  SOIL PH READINGS WERE OBTAINED USING A MODEL HB-2 KELWAY SOIL TESTER. CONTAMINATION WAS LIMITED TO SURFACE AND SHALLOW SUB-SURFACE SOIL VISUALLY CONTAMINATED WITH A DARK COLORED GREASE BASED SLUDGE.  THIS MATERIAL WAS DETERMINED TO BE THE SPENT SULFURIC ACID SLUDGE BY ITS LOW PH READING. ALL SOIL PH READINGS TAKEN FROM LOCATIONS ADJACENT TO THE VISUALLY CONTAMINATED AREA WERE NORMAL.  SEE ATTACHMENT A FOR LOCATION OF CONTAMINATRED AREA AND ADJACENT SOIL PH READINGS. ONCE THE CONTAMINATED AREA HAD BEEN DEFINED, TIER PROCEEDED TO MANUALLY REMOVE AND DRUM THE SPENT SULFURIC ACID SLUDGE AND SURROUNDING SOILS.  THE AMOUNT OF CONTAMINATION TO BE REMOVED EXCEEDED THE CAPACITY OF DRUMS BROUGHT BY TIER PERSONNEL.  ARRANGEMENTS WERE MADE TO RETURN THE FOLLOWING WEEK WITH A SMALL EXCAVATOR AND ADDITIONAL DRUMS AND PLASTIC LINERS TO COMPLETE REMOVAL AND DRUMMING OF SPENT SULFURIC ACID SLUDGE AND ASSOCIATED SOILS. ON MARCH 3, 1992 TIER RETURNED TO COMPLETE THE REMOVAL AND DRUMMING OF SPENT SULFURIC ACID SLUDGE FROM THIS SITE.  IT WAS ESTIMATED THAT 15-20 GALLONS OF ACID WAS SPILLED AT THIS SITE BEFORE FINAL CLEAN-UP WAS INITIATED.  THIS 15-20 GALLONS APPEARS TO HAVE BEEN AN ACCURATE ESTIMATION OF MATERIAL SPILLED.  FIVE (5) 55 GALLON DRUMS WERE GENERATED AS A RESULT OF THIS PROJECT.  THE FIVE DRUMS WERE STAGED ON THE SHOULDER OF I-95 SOUTH TO AWAIT PICKUP AT A LATER DATE. MIKE RYBACKI OF PADER REQUESTED SOIL SAMPLING OF THE CONTAMINATED AREA TO CONFIRM CLEANUP.  THREE (3) SOIL SAMPLES WERE EXTRACTED FROM THE SURFACE TO 1' OF DEPTH IN THE IMMEDIATE VICINITY OF THE CONTAMINATED AREA AND ANALYZED FOR TOTAL PETROLEUM HYDROCARBONS (TPH).  SOIL SAMPLES WERE CONTAINED IN 500 ML JARS WITH TEFLON-LINED LIDS AND PRESERVED IN ICE TO AWAIT PICKUP BY LANCASTER LABORATORIES.  TOTAL PETROLEUM HYDROCARBONS WERE NOT DETECTED IN ANY OF THE SOIL SAMPLES.  SEE ATTACHEMENT B FROM COPIES OF ANALYTICAL RESULTS AND WHERE THESE SAMPLES WERE EXTRACTED AT THE SITE. THE FIVE (5) DRUMS OF SPENT SULFURIC SLUDGE AND SOIL WERE TRANSPORTED AND DISPOSED AS A NON-HAZARDOUS SOLID BY DELAWARE CONTAINER CO. ON MARCH 10, 1992.  SEE ATTACHEMENT C FOR A COPY OF THE DISPOSAL MANIFEST.  MIKE RYBACKI OF PADER WAS CONTACTRED AND INFORMED ON MARCH 11, 1991 THAT THE CLEAN-UP ACTIVITIES AT THIS SITE WERE COMPLETE.

column42: HAZARDOUS SUBSTANCE, LIQUID OR SOLID, N.O.S. OR ORM-E, LIQUID OR SOLID, N.O.S.
column168: ON FEBRUARY 20, 1992 CLEAN HARBORS OF KINGSTON, INC. WAS DELIVERING A LOAD OF POLYCHLORINATED BIPHENYL CONTAMINATED SOIL IN A DUMP TRAILER.  UPON ENTERING THE CHEMICAL WASTE MANAGEMENT (CWM) FACILITY LOCATED AT 1550 BALMER ROAD IN MODEL CITY, NY A REPRESENTATIVE FROM CWM OBSERVED WHAT HE FELT WAS PRODUCT ESCAPING FROM THE REAR DOOR OF THE VEHICLE (APPROXIMATELY 8 OUNCES).  AT THIS POINT CWM CONTACTED THE NEW YORK DEPARTMENT OF ENVIRONMENTAL CONSERVATION (NYDEC) WHO DISPATCHED AN INVESTIGATING OFFICER.  THE DRIVER OF THE VEHICLE WAS INFORMED OF THIS AND HE IMMEDIATELY NOTIFIED CLEAN HARBOR'S NATIONAL TRANSPORTATION GROUP.  CLEAN HARBORS IMMEDIATELY NOTIFIED THE NYDEC AND WAS TOLD THAT CWM HAD ALREADY MADE THE REQUIRED NOTIFICATION.  REPRESENTATIVES FROM THE MODEL CITY FACILITY PLACED A POLY SHEETING UNDER THE VEHICLE TO CATCH ANY ADDITIONAL LIQUID THAT MIGHT LEAK.  THE CLEAN HARBOR DRIVER STATED THAT AFTER THREE AND ONE HALF HOURS, NO ADDITIONAL MATERIAL WAS COLLECTED.  UPON THE ARRIVAL OF THE OFFICER FROM NYDEC, CLEAN HARBORS OF KINGSTON INC WAS ISSUED AN ORDER OF CONSENT (BU-0130-0891) AND WAS ORDERED TO PAY A $1000.00 FINE. CLEAN HARBORS, INC. BELIEVES THAT THE LIQUID OBSERVED TO BE DRIPPING FROM THE REAR DOOR WAS IN FACT RAINWATER/MELTING ICE THAT HAD COLLECTED IN THE FOLDS OF THE TARP THAT WAS COVERING THE LOAD AND THAT THE SEAL OF THE REAR DOOR WAS NOT COMPROMISED.  IN ORDER TO INSURE THAT THIS DOES NOT HAPPEN AGAIN, CLEAN HARBORS WILL INSTRUCT THOSE INDIVIDUALS RESPONSIBLE FOR PREPARING SHIPMENTS OF WASTE MATERIAL TO INSURE THAT THE TARP IS FREE FROM ANY FOLDS OR CREASES THAT COULD RETAIN MOISTURE PRIOR TO RELEASING THE TRUCK.  ALL GASKETS USED IN ALL DOORS ASSEMBLIES WILL BE VISUALLY INSPECTED AND REPLACED IF FOUND TO BE DEFECTIVE.

column168: VII & VIII ABOVE.  THERE WAS NO PACKAGING FAILURE OF ANY KIND ASSOCIATED WITH THIS INCIDENT.  THIS SPILL RESULTED FROM HUMAN ERROR.  OUR DRIVER WAS DISPATCHED WITH A LOAD OF GAS TO BE DELIVERED TO UNDERGROUND STORAGE TANKS AT A CONVENIENCE STORE.  WHEN OUR DRIVER ARRIVED AT THE STORE, HE MEASURED THE AVAILABLE ROOM IN THE BELOW GROUND TANK AND FOUND THAT HE HAD MORE REGULAR UNLEADED GAS ON OUR TANK TRUCK THAN WOULD FIT IN THE STORE'S TANK. THERE ARE TWO REGULAR UNLEADED TANKS MANIFOLDED TOGETHER AT THE STORE. OUR DRIVER CLAIMS HE TURNED AWAY FROM THE REGULAR UNLEADED TANKS TO UN-HOOK THE PREMIUM UNLEADED WHEN THE REGULAR UNLEADED OVERFILLED AND SPRAYED OUT ONTO THE PARKING LOT.  SPILL WAS CONTAINED TO PARKING LOT AND REMOVED WITH CLAY ABSORBENTS.  THE NEW YORK STATE DEPT. OF ENVIRONMENTAL CONSERVATION WAS NOTIFIED AND THEY ASSIGNED A REFERENCE #9112012 TO THE INCIDENT.  OUR DRIVER WILL BE DISCIPLINED & RE-TRAINED ON PROPER UNLOADING TECHNIQUES.

column168: ON FEB. 12, 1992 AT APPROXIMATELY 0930 HOURS, BIRMINGHAM SOUTHERN RAILROAD TRAIN CREW WAS IN PROCESS OF COUPLING ONE BOXCAR AND THREE TANK CARS TO 36 EMPTY HOPPERS ON THE BESSEMER/ENSLEY RUNNING TRACK. HIS FACE BEGAN TO STING.  REALIZING WHAT HAD HAPPENED, HE WENT TO YARD OFFICE AND WASHED HIS FACE, ARM AND NECK.  HE WAS TRANSPORTED TO WORKWISE WHERE HE WAS EXAMINED BY DR. C. SZABO. MR. JAMES SIMS, A CARMAN WITH THE BIRMINGHAM SOUTHERN RAILROAD COMPANY CAR SHOP DEPT. WAS CALLED TO INSPECT TANK CAR PLCX 113029.  MR. SIMS FOUND A MANUAL VENT VALVE SLIGHTLY OPEN.  HOWEVER, THE PLUG ON THE END OF VALVE WAS NOT IN PLACE ALLOWING A VERY SMALL AMOUNT OF ACID TO ESCAPE.  PLUG WAS PLACED IN VALVE AND CAR WAS SPOTTED FOR UNLOADING.  SEE COPY OF TRAINMANSTER J. M. D'ALESIO DETAILED REPORT WHICH IS ATTACHED.

column17: CARMAN J A TRUCKING CO INC
column168: VII & VIII ABOVE.  NO PACKAGING FAILURE OF ANY KIND ASSOCIATED WITH THIS INCIDENT.  THIS WAS BULK DELIVERY OF HOME HEATING OIL TO BORST OIL COMPANY WHO RE-DISTRIBUTES THE OIL INTO HOME DELIVERY TRUCKS. INVESTIGATION INTO THE SPILL LOADING HIS TRUCK.  WHEN WE ARRIVED WITH A TRACTOR TRAILER LOAD TO PUMP OFF, OUR DRIVER OPENED THE  VALVES FOR DELIVERY TO THE BULK TANK UNAWARE THAT ON THE OPPOSITE SIDE OF THE FACILITY THE FUEL OIL HE WAS PUMPING WAS COMING OUT THE TOP LOADING ARM AS WELL AS GOING INTO THE STORAGE TANK.  AS SOON AS OUR DRIVER SAW THE OIL ON THE GROUND HE SHUT DOWN THE PUMP & NOTIFIED AND ASSIGNED A REFERENCE #911445 TO THIS INCIDENT.  THEY ALSO MONITORED THE CLEANUP PROCESS. CERTIFIED #P 026 532 356

column168: THE DRIVER PICKED UP THE LOAD AT DETROIT, MICH 2-20-92 AND IT WAS TO BE DELIVERED TO THE CUSTOMER THE NEXT DAY, WHICH WENT PAST THE TERMINAL.  HE STOPPED AT THE ZANESVILLE GARAGE TO CHECK HIS TIRES, THEN CHECKED THE CATALIC HEATER IN THE TRAILER.  WHILE IN THE TRAILER HE DISCOVERED A SMALL AMOUNT OF WETNESS ON THE TRAILER FLOOR.  FURTHER CHECKING HE DISCOVERED A SMALL LEAK FROM A DRUM AND WAS LEAKING AROUND A SEAM ABOUT 2" DOWN FROM THE TOP.  HAROLD MILEY AND RICK BARR WERE CALLED AT HOME AT ABOUT 10:00 PM AND BOTH RESPONDED TO CHECK TO LOAD. THE EMERGENCY PHONE NUMBER WAS OBTAINED FROM THE BILL OF LADING AND A CALL WAS PLACED TO CHEMTREC #800-424-9300.  THE CALL WAS ACCEPTED BY JOE DENUM WHO GOT IN TOUCH WITH THE SHIPPER.  FIRST CONTACT WAS MADE WITH #2 PERSON ON THE CALL LIST, WANE WALKER, A FEW MINUTES LATER #1 PERSON ON THE LIST, GABRIAL BENET ANSWERED THE CALL.  HE GAVE THE FOLLOWING INSTRUCTIONS.  HE ADVISED TO SOAK UP THE SPILLAGE WITH ABSORBANT MATERIAL AND PUT IT IN A PLASTIC BAG & SHIP IT BACK WITH LEAKING DRUMS. GABRIAL BENET ADVISED TO PUT THE LEAKING DRUMS IN A SALVAGE DRUM AND SHIP THEM BACK TO HIM.  HE SAID NOT TO BE TOO CONCERNED WITH THE FUMES, BUT USE GLOVES AND AVOID GETTING ANY SUBSTANCE ON TEHESKIN, IF ANY CLOTHING IS DAMAGED SEND IT BACK ALSO. SINCE THE MATERIAL WAS HAZARDOUS SUBSTANCES AND A REPORTABLE QUANTITY A CALL WAS PLACED TO THE US COAST GUARD NATIONAL RESPONSE CENTER, WASHINGTON, DC PHONE #800-424-8802.  THE CALL WAS MADE AT MILITARY TIME 0019 2-21-92 AND RECEIVED BY JOE BORDERS.  HE RECORDED THE INFORMATION OF REPORT #107609. THE TRAILER WAS LEFT PARKED IN THE HEATED GARAGE UNTIL ABOUT 0900 2-21-92. THE LOAD WAS REMOVED ARLO BARCLAY, MARK BAKER AND PAT HENNESSEY.  TWO DRUMS WERE FOUND TO HAVE LEAKED A SMALL AMOUNT.  THEY WERE PLACED IN SALVAGE DRUMS.  PICTURES WERE TAKEN OF THE CARGO BY HAROLD MILEY AND FILED IN PICTURE POUCH #92-5. DRIVER - OWNER OPERATOR JAMES R BROMLEY, 10460 UNION HILL ROAD, BLUE ROCK, OH 43720. TRACTOR #1072 TRAILER #4500 - OWNED BY P&D TRANSPORTATION, 1705 MOXAHALA AVE, ZANESVILLE, OH 43701.

column168: TANK CAR CALX 5011 WAS NOTED LEAKING FROM THE TOP AND BOTTOM AREA BY B. LAKE, MANAGER FOR TRAIN INDUSTRY OPERATIONS (MTIO).  MANAGER LAKE ISOLATED CAR AND PLACED CONTAINER UNDER CAR TO CONTAIN ANY FREE FLOWING LIQUIDS. SENIOR SPECIAL AGENT/HAZARDOUS MATERIALS (SSA/HM) D. LOW WAS NOTIFIED AND RESPONDED TO THE INCIDENT.  SSA/HM LOW'S INSPECTION NOTED A SMALL LEAK COMING FROM THE BOTTOM OUTLET CAP AND THE STUFFING BOX VALVE HANDLE MISSING.  FUTTHER INSPECTION DETERMINED THE STUFFING BOX VALVE HANDLE (THREADS BADLY DAMAGED) WAS INSIDE OF THE PROTECTIVE HOUSING LAYING ACROSS THE VACUUM RELIEF VALVE AND LIQUID WAS SPILLING FROM THIS AREA.  THE PACKING GLAND ON THE STUFFING BOX VALVE WAS CROSS THREADED AND DAMAGED WITH LIQUID LEAKING FROM THE AREA AND THE TOP OPERATED, BOTTOM OUTLET VALVE WAS IN THE OPEN POSITION.  SSA/HM LOW SECURED A THREE INCH STEEL COLLAR WITH PLUG OVER THE VALVE AND SECURED THE TOP OPERATED VALVE, REPACKED GLAND, SECURED BOTTOM OUTLET CAP AND REMOVED STUFFING BOX HANDLE WHICH STOPPED ALL LEAKS.  ALL FOUR HEATER COIL CAPS WERE FOUND OFF AND HANGING ON THE SAFETY CHAINS.  SSA/HM LOW SECURED CAPS. JOE DEBMAN OF CHEMTREC AND SHERI PEDRO OF SOLVENT SERVICE WERE NOTIFIED OF THE INCIDENT.  FRA INSPECTOR, TIM DOYLE WAS ON-HAND DURING THE INCIDENT.

STINE WAS NOTIFIED BY MYO STEVE TROUTMAN THAT SWITCH CREW REPORTED PRODUCT SPLASHING FROM THE TOP OF CAR UTLX 78556 DURING SWITCHING OPERATIONS. MANAGER STINE'S INSPECTION DETERMINED THAT BOTH SIDES OF THE CAR HAD DRIED PRODUCT AS A RESULT OF LEAKAGE FROM THE MANWAY NOZZLE.  TWO OF THE EIGHT SWING BOLTS WERE ONLY FINGER TIGHT AND REMAINING SIX WERE NOT WRENCH TIGHT.  MANAGER STINE'S REMOVED THE COVER PLATE AND NOTED THAT NO GASKET HAD BEEN APPLIED TO THE COVER PLATE.  THE SURFACE OF THE NOZZLE WAS CLEANED AND GORTEX FORM GASKET WAS APPLIED WHICH SECURED THE OPENING.  THE LOCKING PIN FOR THE PROTECTIVE HOUSING WAS NOT APPLIED AND WAS HANGING FROM THE SAFETY CHAIN AND THE TWO INCH LIQUID VALVE PLUG WAS LESS THAN WRENCH TIGHT, HOWEVER THE VALVE WAS CLOSED WITH NO EVIDENCE OF LEAKAGE. CHEMTREC, MR. JOE RAZALAN WAS NOTIFIED OF THE INCIDENT.  MR. JIM BRATT OF T-TECH COMPANY NOTIFIED MANAGER STINE AND WAS ALSO FURNISHED INFORMATION ON THE INCIDENT.

column168: SPECIAL AGENT/HAZARDOUS MATERIALS (SA/HM) F.H. LERCH WAS NOTIFIED THAT SOUZ 251272 WAS LEAKING.  CAR WAS SET OUT AND SA/HM LERCH RESPONDED. SA/HM LERCH NOTED A BROWNISH COLORED LIQUID DRIPPING FROM THE UNDERSIDE OF THE TRAILER ONTO THE FLATCAR.  ALL MATERIAL WAS CONTAINED ON THE FLATCAR. KELLER SEAL 6673891 WAS OPENED AND MATERIAL SAFETY DATA SHEETS WERE RETRIEVED.  REVIEW OF THE MSDS AND CALL TO THE SHIPPER, MR. ROBERT ODLE, DETERMINED THAT THREE DIFFERENT PRODUCTS WERE ON THE TRAILER BUT ALL WERE USED FOR WATER TREATMENT AND COULD BE NEUTRALIZED WITH BLEACH AND WATER. SA/HM LERCH NUETRALIZED SPILLED PRODUCT AND CONTACTED NORTH PLATTE CONTRACTORS TO UNLOAD PRODUCT.  DRUM A WAS FOUND EMPTY AND WAS PUNCTURED FROM A SCREW HEAD PROTRUDING FROM THE TRAILER WALL.  DRUM B WAS FOUND HALF FULL AND WAS PUNCTURED FROM A NAIL PROTRUDING FROM THE PALLET IT WAS LOADED ON.  TRAILER WAS NEUTRALIZED, PUNCTURES SEALED WITH SILICONE AND TRAILER INSPECTED AND RELOADED.  SA/HM LERCH SEALED CAR WITH UPC 53178 AND RELEASED.  CHEMTREC, JIM LONG REPORT #13047 AND NEBRASKA ENVIRONMENTAL CONTROL, DAVE TEWES WERE NOTIFIED OF THE INCIDENT.

column168: STATEMENT BY STEVE GROHOL: ON FEBRUARY 3, 1992 A SHIPMENT {AIRBILL NO. 400 8037 6520} WAS STOPPED IN OUR CONTROL AREA AFTER TEAM LEADER BARRY CARLSON DETECTED A STRONG SMELL COMING FROM IT.  I WAS CONTACTED AND OPENED THE BOX TO FIND A CAN LEAKING INSIDE.  AFTER PLACING IN SALVAGE DRUM I CONTACTED MEMPHIS D.G. SPECIALIST {PAT OPENNHEIMER}.  THIS REPORT IS DELAYED BEAUSE IT TOOK OVER 2 WEEKS TO GET A MATERIAL SAFETY DATA SHEET FROM SHIPPER/CONSIGNEE.  AFTER DETERMINING THIS SHIPMENT WAS FLAMMABLE, I CONTACTED FAA SPECIAL AGENT JOHN WHITE WHO INSPECTED THE SHIPMENT ON FEBRUARY 27TH.  PLEASE NOTE THE SHIPMENT WAS NOT MARKED AS HAZARDOUS IN ANY WAY AND THE APPROPRIATE BOX ON AIRBILL WAS NOT CHECKED.
